Right — function-call composition. Same routines invoked twice in-process + symlink helper. Avoids subprocess overhead (fork + exec + pipe + wait), avoids losing rich error info to text-stream parsing, avoids needing the `vc-x1` binary on `PATH` from within itself, avoids state-tracking complexity if the second subprocess fails.

So the implementation shape:

```rust
// clone.rs
fn clone_one(url: &str, target: &Path) -> Result<...> {
    // The shared primitive used by --scope=por (called once)
    // and --scope=code,bot (called twice).
}

fn clone_dual(code_url: &str, target: &Path) -> Result<...> {
    let bot_url = derive_session_url(code_url);
    clone_one(code_url, target)?;
    clone_one(&bot_url, &target.join(".claude"))?;
    symlink::create(target.join(".claude"))?;
    Ok(())
}

pub fn clone(args: &CloneArgs) -> Result<...> {
    match args.scope {
        Scope::Por => clone_one(...),
        Scope::CodeBot => clone_dual(...),
    }
}
```

Same for init's `--scope=por` (per-side primitive) → `--scope=code,bot` (compose two + configs + ochid + symlink).

Ready to update the plan with the compositional framing, or more Qs?

